{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526901"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:27:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:27:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14167"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14167"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.2,0.17,0.07,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6850"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109633"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6850"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14167"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92024"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1098"},{"type":"tags","id":"1569"},{"type":"tags","id":"2913"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15542"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17731"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17945"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17967"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40999"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109633"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 83-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department by his son. He noticed that his father was pale and drowsy when he visited him this morning, and he has been acting very confused and disoriented, which is not normal for him. He last saw his father three days prior, and he was well at this time. The son is able to recall a medical history of hypercholesterolaemia, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and previous cardiac stents. He cannot remember specific medications but remembers his father is on blood thinners and tablets for his blood sugar.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn intravenous cannula is inserted, and bloods are sent to the pathology lab. Whilst his other results are still pending, his venous blood gas immediately returns the following results:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH = 7.32 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3- = 16 mmol/L (22-28)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENa+ = 135 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EK+ = 4 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECl- = 114 mmol/L (95-105)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnion gap = 9 (4-12)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate = 2.8 mmol/L (0.5-2.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKetones = 1.2mmol/L (\u0026lt;0.6 mmol/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s presentation on the basis of this venous blood gas?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diabetic ketoacidosis","Gastroenteritis","Lactic acidosis","Aspirin toxicity","Metformin toxicity"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a normal anion gap metabolic acidosis (\u0027NAGMA\u0027). The anion gap is the difference between measured cations (such as sodium and potassium) and anions (such as chloride and bicarbonate) and is useful in determining the presence of unmeasured anions (such as lactate, ketoacids, toxins etc) in cases of metabolic acidosis. The formula is (Na + K) - (Cl + HCO3), which in this case is (135 + 4) - (114 + 16) = 9, within the normal range (8-16). Sometimes, only the value for sodium will be used due to the comparatively small contribution by potassium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENormal anion gap metabolic acidosis can be caused by gastrointestinal bicarbonate loss, renal tubular acidosis, or certain medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastroenteritis\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause of normal anion gap metabolic acidosis due to the loss of bicarbonate in diarrhoea. This fits with the patient\u0027s presentation of confusion and drowsiness, which can be secondary to dehydration and electrolyte imbalance. It is important to note that it is not uncommon for elderly patients who live home alone to present to hospitals confused and unable to provide complete or comprehensive histories and therefore the lack of a history of diarrhoea or vomiting in a patient who is a poor historian does not preclude this diagnosis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll other answer options would be expected to present with a high anion gap metabolic acidosis (\u0027HAGMA\u0027) due to the accumulation of unmeasured anions and are therefore less likely given this VBG result.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic ketoacidosis (DKA)\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a high anion gap metabolic acidosis due to the accumulation of ketones, an endogenous acid. The presence of a DKA would increase the anion gap, which is not seen in this patient. Additionally, the diagnostic criteria for DKA includes the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum glucose \u0026gt;11 mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVenous pH \u0026lt;7.3 or Bicarbonate \u0026lt;15 mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPresence of ketonaemia/ketonuria\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the blood gas does not meet criteria 2 for the diagnosis of DKA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactic acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E also presents with a high anion gap metabolic acidosis due to the accumulation of lactate. Although this patient has a slightly elevated lactate, it is not high enough to cause a significant anion gap increase, and the overall picture is more consistent with NAGMA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetformin toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E is another cause of lactic acidosis, which would also result in a high anion gap metabolic acidosis. The normal anion gap in this case makes metformin toxicity unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a mixed respiratory alkalosis and high anion gap metabolic acidosis. The absence of a high anion gap and the presence of a straightforward metabolic acidosis without respiratory compensation make aspirin toxicity an unlikely cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Normal anion gap metabolic acidosis can be caused by gastrointestinal bicarbonate loss, renal tubular acidosis, or certain medications.","The anion gap is useful in determining the presence of unmeasured anions in cases of metabolic acidosis."],"references":["Jung, B., Martinez, M., Claessens, YE. et al. Diagnosis and management of metabolic acidosis: guidelines from a French expert panel. Ann. Intensive Care 9, 92 (2019). https://doi.org/10.1186/s13613-019-0563-2","Burger MK, Schaller DJ. Metabolic Acidosis. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482146/","Pandey DG, Sharma S. Biochemistry, Anion Gap. [Updated 2023 Jul 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539757/","Nickson, C. Anion Gap. Life in the Fast Lane. 2020. Available from: https://litfl.com/anion-gap/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92024"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14167"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92024"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-23T15:43:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-23T15:44:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6850"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109633"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":